  "texts": [
    "The performance improves as more concepts are identified, with most models reaching their peak when two nonsensical concepts are used.",
    "This suggests that while the implicit knowledge grounded from multiple concepts provides a richer context, there is a point of diminishing returns beyond which additional concepts contribute less to the overall quality of the generated explanations.Similarly, Fig. 4b, based on the CSE dataset, exhibits the same trends.",
    "Identifying two nonsensical concepts results in a marked increase in performance across BLEU and BERTScore, particularly for larger models like Llama 2 13B and 70B.",
    "Although adding more concepts can sometimes lead to a slight drop in performance, the models still consistently perform better than when no nonsensical concepts are identified.Both datasets underscore that, for most models, identifying and utilizing two nonsensical concepts are optimal for improving explanation quality.",
    "However, in some instances, models may perform differently, with peak performance occurring at a different number of identified concepts.The results indicate that identifying and integrating two nonsensical concepts generally provide the most significant improvement in performance on these datasets."
  ],
